    "premium / discount array",
    "Premium/Discount Array"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price delivery array (PDA) is a collection of technical levels—order blocks, fair value gaps, breaker blocks, inversions, and optimal trade entries—where price is likely to react. Identified after a market structure shift or stop raid, PDAs are situated in premium zones (above equilibrium) for shorts or discount zones (below equilibrium) for longs, often incorporating inducements to frame high-probability entries.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Define the dealing range using the most prominent swing high and swing low; apply Fibonacci to set equilibrium (0.5), dividing premium above and discount below.",
    "Confirm a prior market structure shift or liquidity sweep (stop raid) before seeking PD arrays.",
    "Identify candidate PD arrays (order block, fair value gap, breaker block, inversion, OTE) within the correct half: premium for shorts, discount for longs.",
    "Mark each PD array using its specific formation rules (e.g., opposing close for order blocks, unfilled gap for FVGs).",
    "Prefer nested arrays (e.g., FVG inside an OB aligning with OTE) for confluence.",
    "Validate by waiting for price to retrace into the array and show respect at its edge or half-point with a propulsion block or strong rejection wick.",
    "Prioritize arrays containing an inducement (liquidity) within them and reached only shallowly (not beyond equilibrium).",
    "Reject arrays in the wrong half of the range.",
    "Continuously update ranges and equilibrium as new swing highs/lows form.",
    "In the discount zone (below 0.5), look left for bullish PD arrays (FVG, OB); in the premium zone (above 0.5), look left for bearish PD arrays.",
    "On daily charts, mark order blocks, FVGs, previous day/week highs/lows, swing highs/lows; observe if price touches and closes back inside the range (not closing beyond).",
    "If price touches a low-type PD array (e.g., previous day low, swing low) and fails to close below it, anticipate bullish next day; similarly for high-type arrays.",
    "Inside a mitigation block, look left for order blocks (bullish: bullish candle close; bearish: bearish candle close) or FVGs as PD array candidates, waiting for price to retest.",
    "Identify FVGs as three-candle patterns where the low of the first and high of the third do not overlap; volume imbalances as gaps between open and close of adjacent candles.",
    "Within the OTE zone (0.62–0.79 Fibonacci), look left for FVGs, order blocks, breaker blocks, or volume imbalances overlapping; if order block open is not inside OTE, use its mean threshold (50% of body) as confluent level.",
    "More confluent arrays (e.g., FVG + OB + OTE aligned) increase confidence.",
    "After AMD manipulation leg standard deviation projection, check if equal highs/lows, order blocks, or FVGs overlap with the projection target to validate reliability."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "PD arrays define high-probability entry zones after a market structure shift or liquidity sweep. In bullish order flow, take longs when price retraces into a discount array (below equilibrium); in bearish flow, short at premium arrays (above equilibrium). Entry triggers include retracement into the array, often with an inducement sweep. Place stops beyond the array’s extreme; targets are opposing liquidity or intermediate structures. Confluence from nested arrays improves precision and risk-to-reward. In the Next Day Model, price touching a PD array and closing back inside the range can predict next day direction. Inside mitigation blocks, PD arrays serve as precise entry triggers. In AMD framework, PD arrays aligning with standard deviation targets enhance target reliability.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Using a PD array without a prior stop raid, market structure shift, or change in state of delivery confirmation.",
    "Entering longs in premium or shorts in discount (wrong half of the range).",
    "Expecting reactions when price has already pushed beyond equilibrium or fully through the array.",
    "Placing stops too tight within the array instead of beyond its extremes.",
    "Failing to update dealing ranges and equilibrium as new swing highs/lows form.",
    "Overloading with multiple array types causing analysis paralysis; not mastering one.",
    "Ignoring liquidity context (inducements, swing highs/lows) when trading PD arrays.",
    "Expecting reactions during consolidation rather than expansion or retracement.",
    "Identifying arrays only in hindsight without a real-time plan.",
    "Entering near equilibrium instead of deep into discount/premium, resulting in poor risk-to-reward (approx 1:1).",
    "Ignoring dynamic range expansion; failing to update range and equilibrium after new highs/lows.",
    "Holding bias when price touches a PD array but closes beyond the range (breakout).",
    "Judging direction prematurely without waiting for candle close confirmation back inside the range.",
    "Entering directly at the mitigation block edge without finding a specific PD array inside as precise trigger.",
    "Ignoring whether a valid PD array exists inside the mitigation block (e.g., FVG invalidated after close-through).",
    "Not validating PD array with higher timeframe levels (e.g., weekly FVG).",
    "Relying solely on OTE without checking left for other PD arrays, making entry basis weak.",
    "Forcing an order block as confluent when its open is outside OTE, instead of using mean threshold."
  ],
